00:06:11.280 --> 00:06:18.470 align:middle line:90%


00:06:18.470 --> 00:06:20.630 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: It's when the
price and the quantity

00:06:20.630 --> 00:06:23.310 align:middle line:84%
demanded move in
the same direction.

00:06:23.310 --> 00:06:26.600 align:middle line:84%
So if the price of something
goes up, then you want--

00:06:26.600 --> 00:06:29.160 align:middle line:90%
then you buy more of it.

00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:30.410 align:middle line:90%
ROBERT TOWNSEND: That's right.

00:06:30.410 --> 00:06:32.720 align:middle line:90%
OK, perfect.

00:06:32.720 --> 00:06:33.810 align:middle line:90%
Perfect answer.

00:06:33.810 --> 00:06:36.350 align:middle line:84%
So the point is,
the quantity is what

00:06:36.350 --> 00:06:38.750 align:middle line:84%
we have in mind when we
talk about Giffen goods,

00:06:38.750 --> 00:06:44.150 align:middle line:84%
not price times quantity,
not expenditure shares.

00:06:44.150 --> 00:06:47.630 align:middle line:84%
What creates a
Giffen good is a good

00:06:47.630 --> 00:06:51.500 align:middle line:84%
which is not normal,
that is to say,

00:06:51.500 --> 00:06:56.470 align:middle line:84%
where expenditures are
falling, relatively speaking,

00:06:56.470 --> 00:06:58.890 align:middle line:90%
as we increase income.

00:06:58.890 --> 00:07:05.440 align:middle line:84%
And the point is there's two
effects of price changes.

00:07:05.440 --> 00:07:08.830 align:middle line:84%
Engel's law is about
income changes.

00:07:08.830 --> 00:07:12.160 align:middle line:84%
Giffen's paradox is
about a price change.

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:13.900 align:middle line:84%
But the price
change can be broken

00:07:13.900 --> 00:07:16.540 align:middle line:84%
into two pieces,
the substitution

00:07:16.540 --> 00:07:20.470 align:middle line:84%
effect and the
consequent income effect.

00:07:20.470 --> 00:07:26.330 align:middle line:84%
And the substitution effect
does mean that as price goes up,

00:07:26.330 --> 00:07:28.910 align:middle line:90%
you would demand less.

00:07:28.910 --> 00:07:32.310 align:middle line:84%
But the income effect means
that as price goes up,

00:07:32.310 --> 00:07:35.040 align:middle line:84%
you have effectively
less income.

00:07:35.040 --> 00:07:37.550 align:middle line:84%
And if it's a
necessity, then you're

00:07:37.550 --> 00:07:40.880 align:middle line:84%
going to spend relatively
less on that good.

00:07:40.880 --> 00:07:46.250 align:middle line:84%
So that's the-- tends to
make the quantity go down,

00:07:46.250 --> 00:07:49.060 align:middle line:84%
so it's about income
effect dominating

00:07:49.060 --> 00:07:56.740 align:middle line:84%
the price effect with
implications for quantities.

00:07:56.740 --> 00:07:58.340 align:middle line:90%
I hope that's helpful.

00:07:58.340 --> 00:08:01.420 align:middle line:84%
Another way to say this is when
we look at income expansion

00:08:01.420 --> 00:08:04.300 align:middle line:84%
paths just changing
income, we're not

00:08:04.300 --> 00:08:08.580 align:middle line:90%
moving the price around at all.

00:08:08.580 --> 00:08:11.990 align:middle line:84%
And we are assuming somehow
you can make comparisons

00:08:11.990 --> 00:08:15.110 align:middle line:84%
across to different
income groups,

00:08:15.110 --> 00:08:17.370 align:middle line:84%
that they're all
facing the same prices.

00:08:17.370 --> 00:08:20.870 align:middle line:84%
It's just that some people have
more income than others, which

00:08:20.870 --> 00:08:24.620 align:middle line:84%
is effectively what would
happen for a given individual

00:08:24.620 --> 00:08:30.580 align:middle line:84%
if somehow a poor individual
were given more income.

00:08:30.580 --> 00:08:34.630 align:middle line:84%
But it's all about moving income
around in the cross-section

00:08:34.630 --> 00:08:37.900 align:middle line:84%
or as if, over time
for a given individual,

00:08:37.900 --> 00:08:40.419 align:middle line:84%
holding the prices
fixed, whereas the Giffen

00:08:40.419 --> 00:08:45.250 align:middle line:84%
good has to do entirely
with just changing prices.

00:08:45.250 --> 00:08:48.130 align:middle line:84%
Income changes only as a
consequence of the price

00:08:48.130 --> 00:08:52.488 align:middle line:84%
change, and the Giffen
good is about quantity.

00:08:52.488 --> 00:08:53.530 align:middle line:90%
So I hope that's helpful.

